European debt write-off is unavoidable
Berkeley -- "That is only the Greek crisis", "That is only the crisis of Greece and Ireland", people used to think that way, but now it can't be that way, because it's obviously already a crisis of the euro zone.
Fighting it is both easier and more difficult than people thought
The economic logic of this crisis is quite simple
Greece's fiscal problems exist
Ireland has problems with its banking industry.
Portugal has problems with its private debt market.
Spain has problems in all the above aspects.
Although the details are different, the conclusion is the same: these countries will all have to go through the painful process of reducing spending.
To offset the side effects of the tight policy, the usual method is to combine domestic spending cuts and a depreciation of the domestic currency.
Devaluation will enhance export competitiveness, which is essentially relying on external demand to offset internal demand.
However, these countries are all European Union countries, they do not have an independent currency that can be devalued, so they can only use internal devaluation as a substitute for external devaluation.
They must reduce wages, pensions and other costs to enhance export competitiveness, achieving the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, the determination of these crisis countries to tighten their belts is not small.
However, there is one economic variable that has not changed with the adjustments of other variables, which is the debt of both the public and private sectors.
The face value of the accumulated government debt has not changed, and the bank debt – excluding some debt owed to junior creditors – has not changed much either.
This simple fact has put internal devaluation in a contradictory situation: the more wages and other costs are cut, the relatively heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes.
The heavier the burden of debt, the more public spending needs to be cut and taxes increased to cope with the debt of the government and its defenders (such as banks).
This, in turn, requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the burden of debt, and so on in a vicious cycle, dragging the economy into a quagmire of recession.
Therefore, for internal devaluation to be effective, we must find a way to reduce the value of the debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted to equity, and banks with insufficient assets to cover their debts should be abolished.
Subprime debt must also be written down.
Policy makers do not want to take this route, which is understandable.
The sanctity of contracts.
Government is worried about losing credibility in the financial market.
If the debt holders are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, debt write-off will only harm other countries.
These concerns are not unreasonable, but we should not draw an unreasonable conclusion from them.
The only way out is either internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose between the two.
They have consistently ruled out external devaluation.
But internal devaluation inevitably requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is both illogical and unreasonable.
Debt restructuring is a simple and clear operation.
The government can issue a batch of debt rights, with a face value that is discounted at a certain ratio from the current debt face value.
Debt holders can choose to either stick to exchanging their bonds at face value, but with a later maturity date and lower interest rates; or accept bonds with a discounted face value, but with an earlier maturity date and higher interest rates.
This is not some cutting-edge technology, people have done it before.
But to do it successfully, there are three prerequisites.
First, to guarantee the safety of new bonds to debt holders.
Someone has to come out to guarantee this batch of bonds.
20th century 80s, when implementing the Brady Plan to restructure Latin American debt, the U.S. Treasury Department played the role of "guarantor brother."
Today, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, each country must act in unison.
Otherwise, a country's restructuring will raise expectations for other countries, causing a transmission effect.
Finally, banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring must have their balance sheets solidified.
These banks need to go through a real stress test, not the routine propaganda in the early year.
If the debt restructuring implies that the capital is insufficient, it needs to be a full-scale debt-to-equity conversion for the relevant banks.
If this is still not enough, the government must inject capital into the relevant banks.
This requirement also needs countries to act in unison.
Once the banks' balance sheets are solidified, there is a possibility to restructure home mortgages, bank debts and other private sector debts without shaking the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires decisive leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that their banks have a large risk exposure in the debt of eurozone peripheral countries, and the situation is urgent.
They must convince their backroom bosses and the voters that using public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since they are urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, they must accept the responsibility of providing guarantees.
One word, European leaders, especially German leaders must make the consequences more serious – – not doing so will bring about a calamity.
Because the fact is just like that.
